As a first step, here is a map that will allow translating a card name to it&#39;s numeric position relative to the other card names. Ace is ranked the highest in position 13, while the Two card is ranked lowest in position 1.
```
static Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; positions = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
static {
    positions.put(&quot;Two&quot;, 1);
    positions.put(&quot;Three&quot;, 2);
    positions.put(&quot;Four&quot;, 3);
    positions.put(&quot;Five&quot;, 4);
    positions.put(&quot;Six&quot;, 5);
    positions.put(&quot;Seven&quot;, 6);
    positions.put(&quot;Eight&quot;, 7);
    positions.put(&quot;Nine&quot;, 8);
    positions.put(&quot;Ten&quot;, 9);
    positions.put(&quot;Jack&quot;, 10);
    positions.put(&quot;Queen&quot;, 11);
    positions.put(&quot;King&quot;, 12);
    positions.put(&quot;Ace&quot;, 13);
}
```

Here&#39;s a simple usage below. All it&#39;s doing is calling `Ararys.sort()` with a compartor that looks up each card name in the `positions` map. Note that the &quot;cards&quot; array is just the card names and not card+suit like you posted (so &quot;Ace&quot;, and not &quot;Ace spades&quot;):
```
public static void main(String[] args) {
    String[] cards = {
            &quot;Ace&quot;,
            &quot;Five&quot;,
            &quot;Four&quot;,
            &quot;King&quot;,
            &quot;Queen&quot;
    };

    System.out.println(&quot;before sort: &quot; + Arrays.toString(cards));
    Arrays.sort(cards, Comparator.comparing(o -&gt; positions.get(o)));
    System.out.println(&quot; after sort: &quot; + Arrays.toString(cards));
}
```

